Python List Methods
Python lists are versatile collections that support a variety of built-in methods for modification and analysis:

Adding Elements:


append(): Adds a single item to the end of a list.

extend(): Adds all elements from an iterable to the end of a list.


insert(index, element): Inserts an item at a specific position.

Removing Elements:


remove(element): Removes the first instance of a specific value.


pop([index]): Removes and returns the item at a given index or the last item if no index is specified.


clear(): Deletes all items from the list.


del: A statement used to delete items by index or slice.

Organizing and Searching:


sort(): Arranges list items in ascending or descending order.


reverse(): Flips the order of elements in place.


index(element): Finds the first index of a specific value.


count(element): Returns the number of times an item appears in the list.

Other Utility Methods:


copy(): Creates a shallow copy of the list.


enumerate(): Provides both index and value during iteration.


zip(): Pairs elements from multiple lists together.


map() and filter(): Used to apply a function to all items or filter items based on a condition.

Python String Methods
Strings in Python come with numerous methods for formatting, searching, and validating data:

Case Conversion:


lower() / upper(): Converts the entire string to lowercase or uppercase.


capitalize(): Capitalizes only the first letter.


title(): Capitalizes the start of every word.


swapcase(): Inverts the case of all letters.

Searching and Checking:


find(sub) / rfind(sub): Locates the first or last index of a substring.


startswith(sub) / endswith(sub): Checks if a string begins or ends with a specific value.


Boolean Checks: Includes isalnum(), isalpha(), isdigit(), islower(), isupper(), and istitle() to verify string content types.

Modification:


strip() / lstrip() / rstrip(): Removes whitespace from both or specific sides of a string.


replace(old, new): Swaps specified substrings for new ones.


split(): Breaks a string into a list based on a separator.


join(list): Connects list elements into a single string using a separator.

Formatting and Padding:


zfill(width): Pads the start of a string with zeros.


center(width): Centers a string within a specified width.


format(): Inserts values into a string placeholder.
